The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator who could make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about Czech operators being one of the most expensive in Europe.
After all, it was confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the SMS price was higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to get into a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration of over 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators are happy to claim that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has expressed several times that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network does not seem to have much chance anymore (almostly, he would probably find no more frequency).
But there is one more option - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has just brought significant price reductions, which the classic operators had to respond to.
In the United Kingdom, however, there were similar voices to ours before Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market.
But it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobileking in Poland.
In just six months, more than 100,000 customers managed to get this operator and become the fifth largest operator there.
The Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, U:phone, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to work effectively, it is enough for them to have much less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMSs, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
In this way, Tesco Mobile, in the UK, offers at least half as cheap SMS as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move and a bet on an unsharp target group.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative men choose Mobile - an operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept like that in Poland could catch up with us.
It is doubted by the press secretary of Vodafona Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, without chance, they call mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobile.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," she said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, a press spokesperson of the financial group Penta.
It has indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from developing.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been covered by the GTS Novera Group for a long time, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already made progress in the negotiations," says the press secretary of the Group Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's for a better time.
It seems from unofficial information that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to the end of the year.
For the time being, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no entity has addressed us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department Telefónika O2 said.
Other operators are also referred to the specificity of the Czech market.
The T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová provides in rare agreement with the expression O2: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually advantageous business project on which it would be possible to further build."
And he adds: "In the T-Mobile network, it's hard for some virtual operator to show up by the end of the year.
At this point we would have to have a specific agreement on the table in order to be able to think in this short horizon."
Vodafone insists more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says, "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
That's what we consider the most profitable in terms of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafon in this area is to find a partner for the construction of a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
Mobile operators can easily be understood, entering another operator would mean increasing competition, leading to a drop in prices, and hence a decrease in their profits.
Why, then, make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that, when it comes to operators, they can pull a rope, even the tows around the rise of U:phone.
Probably the biggest pressure towards the CTÚ went at the time of the creation of U:phone from T-Mobile.
This is witnessed by publicly available information from the CTÚ website.
Now, however, the U:phone fits as an argument as to why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
In view of this approach, however, mobile operators are directly concerned by the total disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not only the position of the Czech Republic, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other advanced countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Competition Protection Office (UOHS).
But he has taken his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible once the contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the hire of the necessary infrastructure has been concluded.
No such agreement has been concluded until now, since the offer of potential candidates is unlikely to be interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristián Chalupa from the UOHS External Relations Department in response to our question.
The representatives of the operators thus formulated may not be surprised.
It is more than a reasonable one from the office to represent the interests of consumers and, inter alia, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "For the abroad where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the drop in prices is not one of the interests of the ÚHS.
In fact, it is shocking to think about the whole case that the three mobile operators have a touching relationship that results from their reactions.
