"The Office has not found signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case, and therefore has no reason to interfere.
None of the operators have a dominant position and therefore have adequate responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to meet the telecommunications regulator," he said.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of dispute.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the OCT, according to which telecommunications is the single market from a competitive point of view.
