Interview - Blood, which is again certain
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of the founding and its president, Dr Francine Décary, was rightly pleased because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after a scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is commonly known, the state blood reserve managed by the Red Cross Transfusion Department of Canada was contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave, the Canadian government opened a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and of making recommendations not to reoccur.
While Judge Krever missed the report, some provinces put in motion a committee with the aim of planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québek, this role was played by Gélinea's committee.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was supposed to run Québec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started his activities in 1998, only 38% of the people still had confidence in the Québeck blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was daunting.
With continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and work in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he says, proudly, that at the beginning of 2008 Hema-Québek trusted almost 94% of the Québek population.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, we have seen many cases of human disease of mad cow in Europe, a new variant of disease called Creutzfeldt-Jacob’s disease," says the woman who has led society since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krevere and Gélineau report, according to which, if we do not know this and when there is a risk of serious illness spread, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jacob’s disease, which is characterised by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take exclusion measures.
In April 1999, therefore, we rejected blood from people who have been staying in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely demonstrated that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping to the principle of prudence made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market for the detection of HIV: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests have allowed to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of the patient's infection and the moment when the first viruses may be discovered by our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period for less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowing it, and without even finding out.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is today exposed to one of 12 million people.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for HIV to be transmitted through the blood product.
I believe that today we can completely obtain or prescribe blood transfusions necessary to heal," says the head of management of Héma-Québek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what kind of disease the system might be.
Just last year, a virus of chiungunya appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transferred to the blood by stabbing insects.
We need to be constantly cautious," Dr. Décary continues, stressing that, in addition to safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for a blood donor network, which on average consists only of 3% of Québecans allowed to donate."
Every healthy person aged at least 18 years, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, which means six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not on average accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud colds are running, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, the donors’ network should be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and cannot donate blood anymore.
However, convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so indecent today that we will rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary will.
With the annual budget of $297 million Hema-Québec not only supplies blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eye tube and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Québek, which also manages the only public blood bank from the cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord previously regarded as biomedicine waste is flowing with blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousands of blood samples from the cord to the bank, and we assume that we will be taking them over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplantation," says Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all the hospitals in Québek.
