Psychology of trumpeting: why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money overestimating goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been revealed to researchers in Neurology and Economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people do not want to fall in the eBay auction competition, so they would rather pay too high a price.
Research was using an experimental auction to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers planted, the second group participated in the played auction, and using the functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the experimental persons were examined.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in a game of auctioning, the important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole of the brain’s cortex, called the stratum, began to work intensively in losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "security" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible, according to the researchers, to explain the effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striata.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists carried out a financial cross-sectional investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups were biding against one partner.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they came out of the game winning, they would get another $15 reward.
On the other hand, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, always in the fact that one was highlighted by winning and losing.
However, the members of the group playing "anti-crime" were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "winn" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
These have so far explained the phenomena observed in the auctions by the joys of victory and by avoiding risk.
When the neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," said Andrew Schitter, professor of the New York University of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to find a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is reported among the major causes of death.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are being treated because the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, inflammation of the liver and jaundice is symptomatic, but the originators of the disease and the disease caused by them vary from one another.
The hepatitis virus is spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E by digestive tracts (e.g. infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and body fluid viruses (sperma, vaginal secret, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, the vaccine does not exist against virus C.
Signs of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after ingestion of an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, compulsive vomiting.
After this, the skin and eye whites form a jaundice, light stool and darkens the urine. The treatment may take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die of more serious disease, liver cancer, and hepatic cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only every tenth of the infected patients are medically treated.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to hepatic cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected with their disease don't even know, the pathogen destroys liver cells in an intracranial way, and so the first symptoms come in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, regular write-down is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had undergone blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and between people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his or her doctor if he or she notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infectiousity and preventing cancer.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organized worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, its causes and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
