The intelligent car mimics the flight of a man
What would perhaps be the best method of developing the technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not the imitation of obstacles found in the world of nature?
A bee, for example.
The default strategic idea of a surprising project, presented at the Japanese fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan czmelans. It was about how to build a new generation of systems that prevent collisions.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has designed a bio-mimetic robot management system BR23C, a robotized miniiauto equipped with bees characteristics, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all precipitations.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety packaging," explained Kazuhiro Doi, the Director-General of the Trademark for Technology and Research and Development.
The complex eyes play an important role that allows bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions of view.
The engineers were able to copy the function of the complex eye after the idea of a laser distanceometer.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in the field of vision 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing precipitation.
The transmission is captured during a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts to imitating the movement of the bees and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the precipitation immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If it wasn't for that, a robot car could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and project of a robotic car.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and internal layer of safety cover, within which the impact is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not last longer than the blink of the eye.
But unlike bees, this movement can not go up, down, or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown was applied in the case of a robot car.
BR23C uses lithium polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reactions, not the ability to process, but the less storage of data are important.
This mechanism must only process and respond to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need for it to preserve and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, therefore it constantly uses only a memory of a few kilobytes size.
He doesn't need memory of giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing technology for immediate avoidance, which, according to Nissan's estimates, could reach serially produced cars within ten years.
Another possibility of use may be to link the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding in the way of obstacles lying, would lead the motorist to the target set.
