"We are satisfied with the progress made at night and we very much appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said the White House spokesperson Tony Fratto.
In fact, the program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal, in which it was intended to make a total of $700 billion in the purchase of quality securities secured by mortgages.
It is now possible to spend up to half of 700 billion in the first half of the amount, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after the matter is expected to be decided by Congress on Monday, and the Ministry of Finance will buy securities secured by mortgages that are rated as poor, the fate of the remaining 100 billion dollars will depend on the President's decision.
